(9. Why disk warranties are useful at work but not for me at home) Tj
T*
(Source: Chris's Wiki :: blog | Published: 2026-06-12T01:40:54Z) Tj
T*
(Link: https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/tech/DiskWarrantyHomeVsWork) Tj
T*
(I've been using my home desktop for many years now, with a variety of disk drives, and over) Tj
T*
(those years some of those disks have failed \(without data loss, because I use software RAID) Tj
T*
(mirrors\). Some of the time, those failures have happened when the HDD was still under warranty,) Tj
T*
(but despite that I've never bothered to try to return one for a warranty replacement. This is) Tj
T*
(strikingly unlike work, where we routinely return failed drives that are still under warranty.) Tj
T*
(Historically there have been two things that changed my behavior at home. The first is that) Tj
T*
(when a disk drive fails in my home system, my priority has always been to restore redundancy as) Tj
T*
(fast as possible. Sending a drive in for warranty replacement and waiting for the new one would) Tj
T*
(take weeks, and I don't want to run a non-redundant setup for that long, so I've always gone) Tj
T*
(out and bought a replacement drive immediately. The second is that a lot of the time, the) Tj
T*
(failed disk was old enough that the replacement HDD I'd be buying was bigger, which typically) Tj
T*
(meant that I had little immediate use for a smaller than I now wanted warranty replacement) Tj
T*
(drive. \(In retrospect, spare HDDs for backups were one use, but I'm lazy.\) Nei...) Tj
T*
() Tj
